  I built a shell prompt for zsh called capsule using Rust. It uses a resident daemon to calculate and cache the prompt, and benchmarks show it is 3–30 times faster than starship. All of the code was written by a coding agent.
  
  [https://github.com/shuymn/capsule](https://github.com/shuymn/capsule)
  
  ## Why I was dissatisfied with starship
  
  starship is a well-maintained OSS that is easy to install and supports many shells. However, in my usage, there were moments when I had to wait a little after pressing Enter before the shell became usable.
  
  Every time starship generates a prompt, it launches a process and synchronously evaluates all modules, including Git information and toolchain detection. This speed is unnoticeable if you only use lightweight modules, but as the number of modules involving `git status` or command execution increases, the prompt display is delayed accordingly.
  
  I was bothered by the architecture that requires waiting for everything every time, even though the amount of information I need is not that large.
  
  ## Overview of capsule
  
  A Rust-based shell prompt for zsh that works on macOS and Linux.
  
  It looks roughly like this:
  
  ```
  <directory> on <git branch> [indicators] via <toolchain> took <duration>
  at <time> ❯
  ```
  
  ![](https://static.zenn.studio/images/copy-icon.svg)![](https://static.zenn.studio/images/wrap-icon.svg)
  
  While the appearance is close to the starship default, it does not aim for starship compatibility.
  
  It takes only 3 steps to try it out:
  
  1. `brew install shuymn/tap/capsule` to install
  2. `capsule daemon install` to set up the resident daemon
  3. Append `eval "$(capsule init zsh)"` to your .zshrc
  
     - Be careful not to conflict with configurations like starship
  
  Detailed installation instructions and configuration examples are summarized in the README.
  
  ## Design to speed up "time to interactivity"
  
  I did not aim for the absolute fastest simple string rendering, but rather prioritized consistently shortening the time from pressing Enter until the shell becomes interactive.
  
  As mentioned above, starship is designed to return results after waiting for all modules to complete. capsule solves this problem by separating the timing of returns based on the heaviness of the processing.
  
  ### Fast path
  
  Information such as directory, time, command duration, and prompt character can be calculated on the spot. The daemon builds the prompt with only these, returning the first result immediately. By this point, the shell is usable.
  
  ### Slow path
  
  `git status` and toolchain version acquisition are offloaded to the background using `tokio::spawn_blocking`. Once results are available, the daemon notifies zsh, which updates the prompt via `zle reset-prompt`. From the user's perspective, Git branch or toolchain information is added after the initial prompt is displayed.
  
  The slow path results are saved in an LRU cache. The cache key consists of "cwd + config generation + dependency hash," where the dependency hash includes the values of environment variables referenced by the module and the existence of files specified in `when.files`. When a cache hit occurs, it returns immediately while re-verifying in the background, sending an update if the result has changed (stale-while-revalidate). When a calculation for the same cache key is in progress, subsequent requests subscribe to the ongoing result (inflight coalescing), so the daemon load does not increase even if triggered repeatedly.
  
  Let's see how this design affects the benchmarks in the next section.
  
  ## Benchmarks
  
  I use a benchmark harness provided in the repository for measurement. capsule is measured via direct socket communication with the daemon, while starship is measured by launching sub-processes, which is closer to actual prompt usage.
  
  There are two types of workloads:
  
  - outside: Outside of a Git repository. No toolchain detection. A condition with little information contained in the prompt.
  - repo-toolchain: Inside a Git repository with toolchain detection files. A condition closer to an actual development environment involving `git status` acquisition or command execution.
  
  capsule's `repo-toolchain` has two values:
  
  - fast: Until the fast path result is returned. The initial prompt containing only the directory and time.
  - slow: Until the slow path result is reflected. The full prompt including Git status and toolchain information.
  
  Measurement environment:
  
  - macOS: `15.7.4`
  - CPU: `Apple M4 Pro`
  - starship: v1.24.2
  
  | Workload | Tool | p50 ms | p95 ms | vs starship |
  | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
  | outside | capsule | 0.95 | 1.65 | x4.3 |
  | outside | capsule (cached) | 0.14 | 0.42 | x30.0 |
  | outside | starship | 4.05 | 4.65 |  |
  | repo-toolchain | capsule | 0.07 / 4.07 | 0.11 / 6.03 | x170.0 / x2.9 |
  | repo-toolchain | capsule (cached) | 2.01 | 7.56 | x5.8 |
  | repo-toolchain | starship | 11.62 | 12.70 |  |
  
  What stands out is the fast path for `repo-toolchain`. In a situation where starship takes 11.62ms, capsule returns the first prompt in 0.07ms. Looking at the time until the shell becomes interactive, there is a 170x difference.
  
  Even for the full prompt display including the slow path, it is 2.9x faster, and 5.8x faster in situations where the cache is effective. Even in light conditions like `outside`, the elimination of startup costs due to the resident daemon leads to a 4–30x difference.
  
  ## Architecture
  
  The overall structure is simple, involving three components:
  
  capsule daemon(resident)capsule connect(coprocess)zshcapsule daemon(resident)capsule connect(coprocess)zshEvaluate Fast modules(directory, time, duration, character)Shell interactive hereEvaluate Slow modules(git status, toolchain)Get from cacheAsync calculation via spawn\_blockingalt\[Cache Hit\]\[Cache Miss\]opt\[Result changed\]cwd, exit code, duration, cols, keymapRequest (netstring)RenderResultSet PROMPTUpdateDisplay update via zle reset-prompt
  
  ### zsh to capsule connect
  
  zsh passes the current directory, exit code, command execution time, terminal width, and keymap to `capsule connect` using the `precmd` hook. `capsule connect` resides as a coprocess, and the data is passed as tab-separated text. The zsh-side code is about 220 lines and holds no protocol interpretation or logic.
  
  ### capsule connect to daemon
  
  `capsule connect` converts the information received from the shell into netstring format and sends it to the daemon via a Unix domain socket. Communication with the daemon uses typed messages (Request, RenderResult, Update, etc.).
  
  ### Daemon processing
  
  The daemon runs on a single-threaded tokio runtime. When it receives a request, it checks the mtime of the configuration file to hot-reload if necessary, and evaluates enabled modules categorized into fast/slow. It builds and returns the first prompt using only the results of fast modules, while running slow modules in the background.
  
  The prompt layout is fixed to 2 lines (information line + input line). If it does not fit the terminal width, it first omits the directory, and if it is still not enough, it drops segments from the right end one by one. ANSI escape sequences are wrapped in zsh's `%{...%}` to exclude them from width calculation, and the full-width nature of CJK characters is also considered.
  
  ### Daemon management
  
  on macOS, the daemon is managed via launchd socket activation, and on Linux, via a systemd user unit. `capsule daemon install` generates the service definition according to the platform.
  
  ## Differences from starship
  
  While the look is similar, the design philosophy differs.
  
  ### Consistent response speed via resident daemon
  
  Since capsule has a resident daemon, there is no cost of launching a process for every prompt. The cache can also be carried over across processes, so slow path re-calculation does not occur as long as you are in the same directory.
  
  ### Extensibility via custom modules
  
  starship has an abundance of specialized modules for each language and tool. capsule does not lean in that direction, but rather adopts a structure where custom modules are combined to create the display content.
  
  For example, you can define a module that fires only in a certain directory, extract values from environment variables or command results using regular expressions, and embed them into the prompt using format strings.
  
  ```
  [[module]]
  name = "rust"
  when.files = ["Cargo.toml"]
  format = "v{version}"
  icon = "🦀"
  connector = "via"
  style = { fg = "red" }
  
  [[module.source]]
  name = "version" # Becomes available as {version} in format
  env = "RUST_VERSION"
  
  # If there are sources with the same name, they are evaluated asynchronously,
  # and the first one obtained is used.
  [[module.source]]
  name = "version"
  command = ["rustc", "--version"]
  regex = 'rustc ([\\d.]+)'
  ```
  
  ![](https://static.zenn.studio/images/copy-icon.svg)![](https://static.zenn.studio/images/wrap-icon.svg)
  
  If you define multiple sources with the same variable name, they are evaluated in the order of env, file, and command, and the first value obtained is used. Since the command source runs asynchronously, it does not block the prompt display.
  
  Initially, I also prepared built-in modules, but after considering aspects like disabling via user settings and conflict handling, I abolished built-ins. Instead, you can output custom module definitions for Rust, Go, Bun, Node.js, Ruby, and Python in TOML using `capsule preset` (Bun and Node.js are exclusive, with Bun taking priority).
  
  ### Intentionally narrowed scope
  
  Compatibility is not a goal. The configuration system is different, and it cannot read starship configurations directly.
  
  The layout is fixed to 2 lines. It does not support right-alignment, free column layout, or Powerline. This is because it is enough for me; I might add them if needed, but there are no plans currently.
  
  ## 100% Coding Agent
  
  All of capsule's Rust code was written by a coding agent. I cannot write Rust. What I did was design decisions and operation verification.
  
  The agent used was Claude Code (Opus 4.6 1M Context) primarily, and I switched to Codex (GPT 5.4 medium) when the limits were near. More than the difference in model performance, I used Claude Code as the axis for the peace of mind provided by the 1M Context.
  
  The development period was 3 days during a 3-day weekend. I created the repository on Friday evening and arrived at the current form by Sunday morning. The Rust code is approximately 17,600 lines, with 5 crates.
  
  However, it doesn't end with just having the agent write it. I inserted a cleanup phase every time an implementation of one theme was finished. I would clean up the code with Claude Code's `/simplify`, or delete unnecessary tests and implementations. If I didn't do this intentionally, the code would just bloat endlessly.
  
  Especially in a language I am not proficient in, I cannot judge if it deviates from best practices even if I look at the code. I cannot judge if it 'smells.' That is precisely why I needed to build a cycle of cleanup and verification.
  
  To be honest, I have no outlook on maintenance. I have a fear of not noticing if a feature I don't use breaks. That is also one of the reasons why I narrowed the functional scope to my own usage range.
  
  ## Conclusion
  
  I built this for people who, like me, find the shell prompt wait time subtly stressful and don't have that much information they want to display.
  
  Issues and PRs are welcome, but since I cannot maintain features I don't use, the judgment on whether to merge is based on my own usage range. If that stance is okay with you, please give it a try.
  
